Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Scrub typhus has been found to be responsible for acute encephalitis syndrome (AES) in 63 percent of patients admitted to a hospital in northeastern Uttar Pradesh state (1). Similarly, a report in the journal Emerging Infectious Diseases (2), which ProMED-mail posted (3), indicated that the scrub typhus may account for a significant proportion of acute encephalitis syndrome in the northeastern Indian state of Assam. Scrub typhus could also account for many cases of acute encephalitis in other Indian states (4)

However, I noted at the time in the moderator comments (3) that although headache is a common part of the symptom complex of scrub typhus, acute encephalitis or meningoencephalitis, with a history of altered sensorium, seizures or neck stiffness, and abnormal neuroimaging and cerebrospinal fluid findings, complicates a minority of scrub typhus cases (5-7).

Please also see prior ProMED-mail posts that have discussed the occurrence of acute encephalitis complicating scrub typhus (Acute encephalitis syndrome - India (03): (UP) comment 20151011.3707371 and Acute encephalitis syndrome - India (02): (UP) 20151008.3698951).

